1
00:00:05,520 --> 00:00:06,700
I hope that was stimulating.

2
00:00:09,500 --> 00:00:18,700
We come to the tough topic on a gloomy day when we know the fall is here.

3
00:00:20,930 --> 00:00:26,150
We begin our sixth installment this morning in the series called Tough Questions, Honest Answers.

4
00:00:27,030 --> 00:00:30,370
And the question today is put up here like this.

5
00:00:31,050 --> 00:00:34,170
Why would a loving God torture people in hell?

6
00:00:35,430 --> 00:00:39,030
That question, in various forms, is out there in our society.

7
00:00:39,030 --> 00:00:41,410
And people resist the Christian message.

8
00:00:41,410 --> 00:00:48,370
They resist Jesus, they resist all that the church stands for, sometimes because of this

9
00:00:48,370 --> 00:00:58,000
very issue. Bertrand Russell, we've quoted him before, he said this, there is one very serious

10
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:06,650
defect in my mind in Christ's moral character, and that is that he believed in hell. I do not

11
00:01:06,650 --> 00:01:12,810
myself feel that any person who is really profoundly humane can believe in everlasting

12
00:01:12,810 --> 00:01:22,460
punishment. And B.C. Johnson, an atheist, I found this quote, says this, the idea of hell is morally

13
00:01:22,460 --> 00:01:36,320
absurd. Okay, on the flip side, great Christian theologian G.K. Chesterton said years ago that

14
00:01:36,320 --> 00:01:43,700
Hell is God's great complement to the reality of human freedom and the dignity of human choice.

15
00:01:46,220 --> 00:01:49,080
Two worldviews, once again, coming together.

16
00:01:51,180 --> 00:01:53,820
Let's be honest, hell has a lot of problems today.

17
00:01:54,280 --> 00:02:00,940
And I would say that on the one side, it's actually been elevated in our popular culture.

18
00:02:01,020 --> 00:02:05,740
As a student of popular culture, I'm always looking at theological themes within our culture.

19
00:02:05,740 --> 00:02:12,200
One of the things I see right now on film and in television is hell in various descriptions.

20
00:02:12,480 --> 00:02:16,160
We'll see it in these horrible graphic depictions of hell.

21
00:02:16,220 --> 00:02:19,340
And as we head towards the Halloween season, it's even more ripe out there.

22
00:02:19,780 --> 00:02:23,240
You'll see on television and movies demons, monsters, smoke, fire,

23
00:02:23,740 --> 00:02:28,420
Freddy Krueger, if you recall that series of movies, and now a young lady named Buffy.

24
00:02:30,750 --> 00:02:32,110
Some of your children may be watching.

25
00:02:33,720 --> 00:02:35,780
Popular music has toyed with hell for years.

26
00:02:35,780 --> 00:02:37,500
Blue Easter cults sang about the reaper.

27
00:02:37,640 --> 00:02:39,380
Meatloaf talked about a bat out of hell.

28
00:02:40,060 --> 00:02:45,000
And Australian rockers ACDC gave rock classics as Highway to Hell and Hell's Bells.

29
00:02:45,220 --> 00:02:50,480
The concept of hell has been out there and is out there for our public consumption.

30
00:02:51,140 --> 00:02:52,060
It's part of our culture.

31
00:02:52,640 --> 00:02:56,720
But you know, the reality of hell that's in our culture right now is more of a fantasy.

32
00:02:57,040 --> 00:02:59,060
It's something in a scary movie.

33
00:02:59,060 --> 00:03:02,750
or there's this naive notion out there

34
00:03:02,750 --> 00:03:06,990
that hell is some kind of big, raucous party

35
00:03:06,990 --> 00:03:09,690
and that you really don't want to miss it.

36
00:03:09,770 --> 00:03:12,650
Kind of the idea that all of your friends are going to be there

37
00:03:12,650 --> 00:03:16,150
and it's going to be just kind of wine and song forever

38
00:03:16,150 --> 00:03:18,130
and who wouldn't want to miss that?

39
00:03:21,680 --> 00:03:24,240
So while the secular culture talks a lot about hell

40
00:03:24,240 --> 00:03:27,840
and depicts it in films and thinks of it as a party and so on,

41
00:03:27,840 --> 00:03:31,900
the Christian church, in some ways, is more silent on the topic.

42
00:03:31,900 --> 00:03:35,160
And I think the Christian church is embarrassed by the concept of hell

43
00:03:35,160 --> 00:03:40,180
and in some ways feels bullied by the quotes that I shared on the screen earlier.

44
00:03:41,450 --> 00:03:44,250
What does the Bible teach about hell?

45
00:03:45,490 --> 00:03:47,970
A few weeks ago we established in this series

46
00:03:47,970 --> 00:03:53,190
that the Bible is a trustworthy document to communicate to us God's revelation.

47
00:03:53,750 --> 00:03:55,770
Therefore, we're going to search it for a few moments,

48
00:03:56,110 --> 00:04:00,630
get some of the pieces, and begin to digest what does the Bible teach about hell.

49
00:04:01,110 --> 00:04:03,210
And so this morning, we're going to pull from the scriptures.

50
00:04:03,690 --> 00:04:06,290
I'm pulling from Lee Strobel's book, The Case for Faith,

51
00:04:06,670 --> 00:04:08,910
and also a book that's really excellent.

52
00:04:09,010 --> 00:04:10,370
I've referred to it before.

53
00:04:10,750 --> 00:04:12,390
It's called Beyond Death.

54
00:04:13,150 --> 00:04:16,750
And Gary Habermas and J.P. Moreland write in that one.

55
00:04:16,750 --> 00:04:19,650
And they deal with the philosophical and scientific issues

56
00:04:19,650 --> 00:04:22,170
about death and the afterlife.

57
00:04:24,690 --> 00:04:26,410
And so we begin as I talk about hell.

58
00:04:27,030 --> 00:04:29,950
One quote on hell I found interesting was this.

59
00:04:30,230 --> 00:04:32,230
The idea of hell, says one author,

60
00:04:32,330 --> 00:04:36,190
was born of revenge and brutality on the one side

61
00:04:36,190 --> 00:04:38,650
and cowardice on the other.

62
00:04:39,480 --> 00:04:40,220
This author says,

63
00:04:40,320 --> 00:04:43,720
I have no respect for any human being who believes in it.

64
00:04:43,860 --> 00:04:45,660
I dislike this doctrine.

65
00:04:45,940 --> 00:04:46,800
I hate it.

66
00:04:47,020 --> 00:04:48,220
I despise it.

67
00:04:48,400 --> 00:04:50,760
And I defy this doctrine.

68
00:04:52,410 --> 00:04:53,090
And then he finishes,

69
00:04:53,230 --> 00:04:58,730
This doctrine of hell is infamous beyond all power to express.

70
00:05:00,200 --> 00:05:01,700
That was Colonel Robert Ingersoll,

71
00:05:01,700 --> 00:05:09,300
a 19th century fervent opponent of Christ, opponent of the church, and obviously a great

72
00:05:09,300 --> 00:05:18,550
opponent of the concept of hell. In response to that, Kent Wilson said this, and I put it up here

73
00:05:18,550 --> 00:05:27,910
for you, though one may rail and rant, rebel, or rally against it, hell stands like a monolithic

74
00:05:27,910 --> 00:05:35,660
tombstone in Scripture. It is mentioned on more pages of the Bible than heaven. And obviously

75
00:05:35,660 --> 00:05:44,160
the Spirit of God is telling us something that is crucial. Wow. So to begin, let's look

76
00:05:44,160 --> 00:05:49,360
at some Scriptures. Let's get our mind around what the Bible teaches about hell. So the

77
00:05:49,360 --> 00:05:55,470
first thing, the Bible on hell. Here's a sampling. In the book of 2 Thessalonians, we have one

78
00:05:55,470 --> 00:06:01,250
of two summary verses for the concept of hell. And I've put it up here to share with you.

79
00:06:02,020 --> 00:06:06,580
From chapter 1, verses 7 to 9 of 2 Thessalonians, I read from the New Living Translation,

80
00:06:07,140 --> 00:06:13,520
And God will provide rest for you who are being persecuted, and also for us when the Lord Jesus

81
00:06:13,520 --> 00:06:19,480
appears from heaven. He will come with his mighty angels in flaming fire, bringing judgment on those

82
00:06:19,480 --> 00:06:24,780
who don't know God, and on those who refuse to obey the good news of our Lord Jesus. They will

83
00:06:24,780 --> 00:06:31,480
be punished with, notice, everlasting destruction, forever separated from the Lord and from His

84
00:06:31,480 --> 00:06:36,780
glorious power when He comes to receive glory and praise from His holy people. And you will

85
00:06:36,780 --> 00:06:42,480
be among those praising Him on that day, for you believed what we testified about.

86
00:06:44,120 --> 00:06:51,970
A great summary verse, the concept of separation forever. The other verse is found on the lips

87
00:06:51,970 --> 00:06:55,430
of Jesus, Matthew 25. And it says this,

88
00:06:55,430 --> 00:06:59,430
Then the king will turn to those on the left and say,

89
00:07:00,010 --> 00:07:03,250
Away with you, you cursed ones, into the eternal fire

90
00:07:03,250 --> 00:07:07,250
prepared for the devil and his demons. And they will go away into eternal

91
00:07:07,250 --> 00:07:10,970
punishment, but the righteous will go into eternal life.

92
00:07:13,290 --> 00:07:16,910
I think by way of a little note here, that it is instructive that

93
00:07:16,910 --> 00:07:21,530
Jesus talked a lot about hell. In fact,

94
00:07:21,530 --> 00:07:26,710
as you know, there are many people in our world today that regard Jesus as a great teacher. He

95
00:07:26,710 --> 00:07:32,650
may not be God in their minds, but he's certainly a profound and wonderful teacher. But then my

96
00:07:32,650 --> 00:07:39,420
challenge is, what do you do with all of his teachings about hell? If he's a great teacher,

97
00:07:39,460 --> 00:07:44,620
we have to take him seriously. And he talked an awful lot about hell. He said in Matthew 7,

98
00:07:45,040 --> 00:07:50,520
you can enter God's kingdom only through the narrow gate. The highway to hell, he said,

99
00:07:50,520 --> 00:07:56,640
is broad, and its gate is wide for the many who choose the easy way. But the gateway to life

100
00:07:56,640 --> 00:08:06,080
is small, and the road is narrow, and only a few ever find it. Jesus also said this in Matthew 5,

101
00:08:06,120 --> 00:08:12,260
22, But I say, if you are angry with someone, you are subject to judgment. If you call someone an

102
00:08:12,260 --> 00:08:16,780
idiot, you are in danger of being brought before the high council. And if you curse someone,

103
00:08:16,780 --> 00:08:20,060
you are in danger of the fires of hell.

104
00:08:21,770 --> 00:08:26,670
In these images of hell, we get the references to fire and burning.

105
00:08:28,400 --> 00:08:30,740
But the scriptures also state something interesting.

106
00:08:30,840 --> 00:08:35,980
Kind of on the flip side, you see also hell is described as a place of darkness.

107
00:08:36,460 --> 00:08:37,360
Matthew 8, 12.

108
00:08:37,760 --> 00:08:40,920
But many Israelites, for those whom the kingdom was prepared,

109
00:08:41,260 --> 00:08:44,180
will be cast where? Into outer darkness.

110
00:08:45,020 --> 00:08:46,760
Where there's weeping and gnashing of teeth.

111
00:08:48,770 --> 00:08:50,270
In 2 Peter, something similar.

112
00:08:52,160 --> 00:08:55,400
These people are as useless as dried up springs of water

113
00:08:55,400 --> 00:08:57,600
or clouds blown away by the wind,

114
00:08:58,380 --> 00:09:00,340
promising much and delivering nothing.

115
00:09:01,250 --> 00:09:03,190
He's referring to false teachers, and he says,

116
00:09:03,790 --> 00:09:06,850
they are doomed to the blackest darkness.

117
00:09:09,630 --> 00:09:12,370
Well, from those verses and investigating them

118
00:09:12,370 --> 00:09:14,870
at a more deep level, I want to sum up some ideas

119
00:09:14,870 --> 00:09:16,150
you can take away this morning.

120
00:09:16,530 --> 00:09:17,890
And so my second point is this.

121
00:09:17,890 --> 00:09:21,170
What and where is hell?

122
00:09:23,890 --> 00:09:28,550
If people that you are sharing with, whether friends, neighbors, workmates, whatever,

123
00:09:28,890 --> 00:09:33,110
if they resist this idea of hell and they reject Christianity,

124
00:09:33,190 --> 00:09:36,770
we must have a defensible answer about, well, what is hell?

125
00:09:37,070 --> 00:09:40,290
Where is it? And how do we explain it to somebody else?

126
00:09:40,770 --> 00:09:45,680
What we see from these verses is the understanding that hell is described

127
00:09:45,680 --> 00:09:49,720
in a variety of what I would say are contradictory images.

128
00:09:49,940 --> 00:09:55,000
We've got fire and darkness as literal opposites.

129
00:09:56,390 --> 00:09:58,410
If there's fire, there's light.

130
00:09:59,270 --> 00:10:03,970
How can you have fire and darkness at the same time?

131
00:10:06,430 --> 00:10:08,550
What we must understand is this,

132
00:10:10,160 --> 00:10:12,980
that hell is a place of unspeakable horror

133
00:10:12,980 --> 00:10:16,640
that language has a difficult time describing.

134
00:10:18,080 --> 00:10:20,060
But what I discern from these verses

135
00:10:20,060 --> 00:10:26,630
is that this idea of fire communicates the reality of God's judgment

136
00:10:26,630 --> 00:10:30,250
and to appreciate his utter separateness and his holiness.

137
00:10:32,040 --> 00:10:35,420
Now, one of the charges that is leveled against Christianity

138
00:10:35,420 --> 00:10:41,120
is this concept that God sends people to an eternal torture chamber.

139
00:10:41,440 --> 00:10:43,300
And if you can think about a torture chamber,

140
00:10:43,400 --> 00:10:45,820
if you've ever been to Europe and the castles,

141
00:10:45,820 --> 00:10:49,340
you go down the dungeons and you see these instruments of terror

142
00:10:49,340 --> 00:10:52,440
that were used to extract confessions out of people

143
00:10:52,440 --> 00:10:55,800
or to just inflict horrible, awful, prolonged pain,

144
00:10:56,200 --> 00:10:58,060
it's easy to begin to confuse those

145
00:10:58,060 --> 00:11:00,000
and bring those images together with this

146
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:03,080
and think in terms of God somehow sadistically

147
00:11:03,080 --> 00:11:06,300
putting them in the rack and turning the crank forever.

148
00:11:07,550 --> 00:11:08,670
Awful images.

149
00:11:11,160 --> 00:11:13,440
J.P. Moreland of Talbot Seminary

150
00:11:13,440 --> 00:11:16,020
and one who has spoken from this very pulpit

151
00:11:16,020 --> 00:11:17,500
says emphatically in the book,

152
00:11:18,060 --> 00:11:19,300
The Case for Faith, he says,

153
00:11:19,300 --> 00:11:24,020
for one thing, I quote, hell is not a torture chamber.

154
00:11:25,870 --> 00:11:32,970
And he says what hell really is, is the judgment of God in the form of separation from God.

155
00:11:34,180 --> 00:11:37,020
He goes on and says something I think is really fascinating.

156
00:11:37,140 --> 00:11:42,420
As a wonderful philosopher and a great theologian, he says the essence of hell is relational.

157
00:11:43,280 --> 00:11:47,500
Christianity says people are the most valuable things in the entire creation.

158
00:11:47,500 --> 00:11:55,740
If people matter, then personal relationships matter, and hell, he says, is largely relational.

159
00:11:57,560 --> 00:12:00,300
Hell is essentially separation from God himself.

160
00:12:00,680 --> 00:12:09,820
It is exclusion from all that matters, from all value, not only from God, but also from those who have come to know and to love him.

161
00:12:11,520 --> 00:12:16,480
Gary Habermas, in the book Beyond Death, describes hell this way.

162
00:12:16,480 --> 00:12:23,700
He says, hell is the end of a road away from God, away from love, and away from anything of real value.

163
00:12:24,320 --> 00:12:30,920
It is banishment from the very presence of God and from the type of life we were made to live.

164
00:12:31,680 --> 00:12:35,020
Heaven, which is full of God's presence, is a place of supreme happiness

165
00:12:35,020 --> 00:12:40,460
where we cultivate freely chosen relationship with God and others who love him,

166
00:12:40,460 --> 00:12:45,320
where we can grow in our knowledge of and intimacy with God and others who love him,

167
00:12:45,320 --> 00:12:47,840
where we can serve God and others who love him.

168
00:12:48,100 --> 00:12:52,820
And then he says, hell is the opposite of all of that.

169
00:12:57,080 --> 00:13:00,480
Lee Strobel asks Dr. Moreland this question.

170
00:13:02,050 --> 00:13:05,330
Is hell punishment for breaking God's laws?

171
00:13:05,910 --> 00:13:09,010
Or is it the natural consequence of people living a life

172
00:13:09,010 --> 00:13:11,970
where they say they don't care if they're separated from God

173
00:13:11,970 --> 00:13:13,630
and instead want to do things their way?

174
00:13:14,860 --> 00:13:16,780
You got the sense of that in our skit this morning.

175
00:13:18,540 --> 00:13:19,700
Moreland says it's both.

176
00:13:20,470 --> 00:13:22,470
He says, make no mistake, hell is punishment,

177
00:13:22,470 --> 00:13:24,070
but it's not punishing.

178
00:13:24,930 --> 00:13:25,810
It's not torture.

179
00:13:26,410 --> 00:13:28,450
The punishment of hell is a separation from God,

180
00:13:28,730 --> 00:13:30,690
bringing shame and anguish and regret.

181
00:13:31,010 --> 00:13:32,950
And because we will have both body and soul

182
00:13:32,950 --> 00:13:34,390
in the resurrected state,

183
00:13:34,670 --> 00:13:37,670
the misery experienced can be both mental and physical.

184
00:13:38,110 --> 00:13:40,590
But the pain that's suffered will be due to the sorrow

185
00:13:40,590 --> 00:13:44,890
from the final and the ultimate unending banishment from God,

186
00:13:45,330 --> 00:13:47,430
from his kingdom and the good life

187
00:13:47,430 --> 00:13:49,330
in which we were created in the first place.

188
00:13:49,730 --> 00:13:53,910
He says people in hell will grieve deeply for all they've lost.

189
00:13:54,570 --> 00:14:00,470
It's the final sentence that says you refused regularly to live for the purpose for which you were made.

190
00:14:00,910 --> 00:14:04,750
And the only alternative is to sentence you away for all eternity.

191
00:14:05,350 --> 00:14:11,830
So it is punishment, but it's also the natural consequence of a life that has been lived in a certain direction.

192
00:14:13,720 --> 00:14:15,860
We'll come back to some more concepts about hell.

193
00:14:15,860 --> 00:14:20,120
I think that people also want to know, well, okay, where is it?

194
00:14:21,300 --> 00:14:26,460
We tend to think in terms of hell as being sort of down and heaven as being up.

195
00:14:27,790 --> 00:14:30,330
And those are helpful in a four-dimensional universe, perhaps,

196
00:14:30,330 --> 00:14:33,410
but I think we need to realize that the concepts we're dealing with here

197
00:14:33,410 --> 00:14:35,470
are on a whole different plane of existence.

198
00:14:36,270 --> 00:14:40,170
As I shared before, physicists now think there are at least ten dimensions to our universe,

199
00:14:40,590 --> 00:14:43,470
and so when we think in terms of where is this place,

200
00:14:43,550 --> 00:14:46,830
we're talking more about a plane of existence beyond these dimensions

201
00:14:46,830 --> 00:14:51,930
than in thinking in terms of a literal direction north or south.

202
00:14:54,320 --> 00:14:58,300
Well, number four, the question is often asked,

203
00:14:58,660 --> 00:15:02,940
isn't it immoral for God to send people to hell?

204
00:15:04,460 --> 00:15:06,440
I mean, isn't the question phrased this way,

205
00:15:06,520 --> 00:15:10,240
isn't banishment in hell really kind of a cosmic overkill?

206
00:15:10,800 --> 00:15:14,000
That doesn't seem to be a morally correct action.

207
00:15:15,500 --> 00:15:17,760
And I guess I want to come back and say we've got to remember

208
00:15:17,760 --> 00:15:23,560
that God is the most awesome, wonderful, generous, loving being in the entire universe.

209
00:15:24,080 --> 00:15:29,340
And from that position, He has made us as human beings with a free will for a purpose.

210
00:15:29,660 --> 00:15:34,220
And that purpose is this, to relate to God in love and to love others.

211
00:15:35,160 --> 00:15:38,880
And if we fail over and over again to live for that purpose,

212
00:15:39,360 --> 00:15:41,440
for which we were created in the beginning,

213
00:15:41,820 --> 00:15:44,880
that is one who honors us with our free will.

214
00:15:46,370 --> 00:15:49,390
God gives those who resist him what they desire,

215
00:15:49,730 --> 00:15:52,660
and that is separation from God.

216
00:15:55,570 --> 00:15:58,370
From Oxford University, a philosopher, Richard Swinburne,

217
00:16:00,050 --> 00:16:03,750
he gives an interesting defense of this view of hell.

218
00:16:04,690 --> 00:16:06,210
And he asks this question, he says,

219
00:16:06,510 --> 00:16:09,710
why is it that you have to have right beliefs and a good will,

220
00:16:10,090 --> 00:16:12,710
that is, one that desires God, that desires salvation,

221
00:16:12,710 --> 00:16:14,990
that desires heaven, to go to heaven?

222
00:16:15,770 --> 00:16:19,230
Why are people with wrong beliefs and a bad will left out?

223
00:16:19,890 --> 00:16:22,550
And his answer is really twofold, and I share this with you.

224
00:16:22,750 --> 00:16:29,470
He says, heaven is the type of place where people with wrong beliefs and a bad will would not simply fit.

225
00:16:30,650 --> 00:16:34,830
Heaven must be freely and non-coercively chosen.

226
00:16:36,400 --> 00:16:40,860
And Swinburne goes on in the book Beyond Death, and he talks about meaning and happiness.

227
00:16:40,860 --> 00:16:48,000
And he says that the things of deepest happiness are found in successfully pursuing the tasks of supreme value

228
00:16:48,000 --> 00:16:50,880
and being in a situation of supreme value.

229
00:16:51,380 --> 00:16:53,460
Those include a friendship with God,

230
00:16:54,060 --> 00:16:55,460
learning to care for others,

231
00:16:56,200 --> 00:16:57,520
caring for God's creation,

232
00:16:58,060 --> 00:16:59,160
and those kinds of things.

233
00:16:59,420 --> 00:17:02,160
He says, therefore, from that philosophical perspective,

234
00:17:02,360 --> 00:17:04,780
heaven is not a reward for good action.

235
00:17:05,260 --> 00:17:08,120
It is a home, he says, for good people.

236
00:17:08,640 --> 00:17:11,760
It's the kind of place where people who value God

237
00:17:11,760 --> 00:17:14,640
and his people will enjoy.

238
00:17:16,250 --> 00:17:17,490
And on the other hand, he writes,

239
00:17:17,490 --> 00:17:22,550
people with a bad will or people with a good will with false beliefs

240
00:17:22,550 --> 00:17:26,640
about what God, heaven, and good really are will not be suited

241
00:17:26,640 --> 00:17:31,620
for life in heaven. And so we're coming back to this

242
00:17:31,620 --> 00:17:35,840
idea, and Swinburne would agree, that each day we are preparing ourselves

243
00:17:35,840 --> 00:17:39,500
for either being with God or being separated

244
00:17:39,500 --> 00:17:43,920
from Him. The day-to-day decisions that we make, the little choices

245
00:17:43,920 --> 00:17:48,060
are either lining up with God and His purposes and ultimately

246
00:17:48,060 --> 00:17:53,640
to be with him, or we're making little decisions that alienate us from him and from his people

247
00:17:53,640 --> 00:17:58,540
and from all the things he's created us for. We make those decisions as part of our character

248
00:17:58,540 --> 00:18:04,140
on a daily basis, and ultimately we find the conclusion to where those directions will

249
00:18:04,140 --> 00:18:09,930
take us. One is with God, one is without him. To graphically illustrate the best I can come

250
00:18:09,930 --> 00:18:16,030
up with is that great scene from A Christmas Carol. And I'm just using it as a metaphor,

251
00:18:16,030 --> 00:18:21,850
I'm not going to get very literal, but the concept when Jacob Marley comes back and talks

252
00:18:21,850 --> 00:18:27,460
to Ebenezer Scrooge. Do you remember the scene? And if you're here in our Christmas program,

253
00:18:27,560 --> 00:18:31,460
you're thinking of Ron Stevens and Bruce Steele. Ignore that scene for a moment. Just try to

254
00:18:31,460 --> 00:18:36,380
imagine the film, if you will. But go with me on this. Jacob Marley comes back, and what is he

255
00:18:36,380 --> 00:18:43,920
carrying? Those long chains. And in effect, he's saying, I forged these chains in life. And what

256
00:18:43,920 --> 00:18:50,640
he's saying is each step of my life, every decision I made forged a direction and a repercussions

257
00:18:50,640 --> 00:18:58,680
behind me. And he's carrying these chains and he's saying, don't do this Ebenezer. Don't make

258
00:18:58,680 --> 00:19:05,440
these daily decisions that lead you in a direction where you don't want to be. And I think that

259
00:19:05,440 --> 00:19:11,520
concept is communicated there, that we make those decisions on a daily basis. And ultimately heaven

260
00:19:11,520 --> 00:19:16,760
and hell are the different places based on whether you're in Jesus Christ and following

261
00:19:16,760 --> 00:19:21,480
his will and being conformed by the Spirit to be the kind of people that would enjoy

262
00:19:21,480 --> 00:19:27,180
heaven and enjoy God's people and enjoy God. Or you're resisting God, resisting Jesus,

263
00:19:27,400 --> 00:19:33,000
resisting the atonement, and you follow the natural consequences of those decisions that

264
00:19:33,000 --> 00:19:44,420
make you alienated and separated from God. Scholar Donald Blesch says this, hell does

265
00:19:44,420 --> 00:19:50,700
have a punitive aspect to it. And he says, not because God's love is limited, but because it is

266
00:19:50,700 --> 00:19:57,580
unlimited that hell, as well as heaven, is made necessary. God's wrath indeed is not only a

267
00:19:57,580 --> 00:20:03,640
reaction of God's holiness to sin, but also a demonstration of his love, which punishes for the

268
00:20:03,640 --> 00:20:14,040
sake of the sinner. We think about love for a moment, and loving in today's parlance is a warm,

269
00:20:14,040 --> 00:20:20,480
sweet, sentimental notion, abounding in warm fuzziness, yet in some ways devoid of any

270
00:20:20,480 --> 00:20:30,050
backbone. But a pure, good, moral God must be a God of justice. For justice is bound

271
00:20:30,050 --> 00:20:37,300
up in being loving. Without love, or without justice rather, love is just simply sentiment.

272
00:20:37,660 --> 00:20:41,660
It's sweet, but doesn't get you anywhere. Think about it when you're rearing a child

273
00:20:41,660 --> 00:20:45,460
or you're disciplining somebody. Think about it in terms of that. Is it really loving

274
00:20:45,460 --> 00:20:53,730
to let a child do whatever they want, if they want to play on the freeway. It's not a loving

275
00:20:53,730 --> 00:21:01,970
thing to let them do that. Sometimes when siblings are fighting, parents have to execute, if you will,

276
00:21:01,970 --> 00:21:10,440
tough love. Stop. Separate. Go to your rooms. Think about what you're doing. No television.

277
00:21:10,900 --> 00:21:17,140
No CD-ROM tonight, or whatever it is in the contemporary world. Punishment is part of being

278
00:21:17,140 --> 00:21:22,860
loving? Are we really loving if we have no backbone? Are we really loving if there's

279
00:21:22,860 --> 00:21:28,260
no real justice? And so what I'm trying to say is this. I think when you begin to take

280
00:21:28,260 --> 00:21:32,400
those analogies and stretch them out and apply it to the scriptures, you begin to see that

281
00:21:32,400 --> 00:21:39,720
hell is a morally justifiable position. And that when people put to you that hell is morally

282
00:21:39,720 --> 00:21:44,660
absurd, you can now begin to think in terms of, no, there's good reason why in God's

283
00:21:44,660 --> 00:21:54,300
justice, there needs to be a place called hell. But the question comes back, is eternal punishment

284
00:21:54,300 --> 00:22:02,200
for sin committed in a finite world, is that really fair? I mean, here you are, you make a

285
00:22:02,200 --> 00:22:08,020
few mistakes, it's the thought here, and you're punished forever. Again, cosmic overkill, don't

286
00:22:08,020 --> 00:22:16,240
you think? Well, Gary Habermas answers it this way, if people reject an ultimate God who is the

287
00:22:16,240 --> 00:22:22,540
greatest thing that could possibly ever exist, that an ultimate judgment where one pays with

288
00:22:22,540 --> 00:22:31,900
one's life in a final irrevocable sense is also just. Now, as our minds begin to sift through

289
00:22:31,900 --> 00:22:38,310
some of this, other objections begin to arise. And here are some of the classic ones that Strobel

290
00:22:38,310 --> 00:22:41,830
points out, and I think that you will find them if you talk to people about this topic.

291
00:22:43,180 --> 00:22:48,620
And so I lay them out here for you. Number five, couldn't God force everyone to go to heaven?

292
00:22:49,740 --> 00:22:51,680
Do we really have to have this hell thing?

293
00:22:51,800 --> 00:22:55,420
Can't God just make everybody good and get them to heaven?

294
00:22:57,610 --> 00:23:00,270
Can God force the bad to become good?

295
00:23:02,400 --> 00:23:03,600
No, and here's why not.

296
00:23:05,250 --> 00:23:08,170
That would not respect human freedom.

297
00:23:09,300 --> 00:23:15,180
If God was to force us all to go to heaven, that would force us outside of our will.

298
00:23:15,280 --> 00:23:18,540
And God always works within our will that he gave us and created us to have.

299
00:23:18,900 --> 00:23:23,080
Our character, friends, we've talked about, is formed one decision at a time.

300
00:23:24,130 --> 00:23:26,770
If you're going to cultivate false beliefs and do evil

301
00:23:26,770 --> 00:23:30,030
and start a slide away from God that ends in hell,

302
00:23:30,430 --> 00:23:32,570
God respects those human choices.

303
00:23:32,770 --> 00:23:35,890
God respects persons enough to allow their decisions

304
00:23:35,890 --> 00:23:37,970
to take them to the natural consequences.

305
00:23:39,320 --> 00:23:41,320
For God to override human freedom

306
00:23:41,320 --> 00:23:44,260
is actually immoral on God's part.

307
00:23:45,560 --> 00:23:48,000
You see, that kind of action dehumanizes human beings.

308
00:23:48,520 --> 00:23:52,690
It makes us objects and not beings with will.

309
00:23:54,150 --> 00:23:55,750
It treats people as a means to an end.

310
00:23:56,290 --> 00:23:58,310
And that is contrary to God's character.

311
00:23:59,660 --> 00:24:03,080
Therefore, it's morally wrong for God to force everyone to go to heaven.

312
00:24:03,440 --> 00:24:06,500
Okay, then the question comes up, well, if he's not going to make them go to heaven,

313
00:24:06,760 --> 00:24:08,500
how about just snuffing them out?

314
00:24:10,690 --> 00:24:11,770
Why does he just do that?

315
00:24:13,010 --> 00:24:13,970
Well, back to the same issue.

316
00:24:15,320 --> 00:24:18,880
To annihilate people, to sort of cease to have them exist at all,

317
00:24:18,880 --> 00:24:22,220
removes all the physical and the spiritual existence.

318
00:24:22,220 --> 00:24:29,060
but you're doing that to avoid them having the consequences of their choices.

319
00:24:29,860 --> 00:24:32,320
And again, that treats people as a means to an end.

320
00:24:33,380 --> 00:24:34,620
And as we've seen, that's immoral.

321
00:24:35,700 --> 00:24:36,620
Moreland puts it this way.

322
00:24:36,740 --> 00:24:41,860
He says, what hell does is recognize that people have intrinsic value.

323
00:24:42,830 --> 00:24:47,030
If God loves intrinsic value, then he's got to be a sustainer of persons

324
00:24:47,030 --> 00:24:50,550
because that means he is a sustainer of intrinsic value.

325
00:24:51,070 --> 00:24:52,930
He refuses to snuff out a creature

326
00:24:52,930 --> 00:24:55,170
that was made in his own image.

327
00:24:56,190 --> 00:24:57,730
So in the final analysis, he says,

328
00:24:57,810 --> 00:25:00,210
hell is the only legitimate option.

329
00:25:02,280 --> 00:25:03,860
And I think the image I keep getting then

330
00:25:03,860 --> 00:25:06,860
is almost like hell is almost like a quarantine

331
00:25:06,860 --> 00:25:10,860
for those that want to live on their own strength,

332
00:25:11,020 --> 00:25:13,320
with their own will, apart from God.

333
00:25:13,320 --> 00:25:16,040
Then you put them over here.

334
00:25:17,410 --> 00:25:18,370
Okay, here's one.

335
00:25:18,890 --> 00:25:21,590
Why doesn't God then give a second chance?

336
00:25:24,580 --> 00:25:26,640
Well, the Bible says some interesting things about that.

337
00:25:26,700 --> 00:25:29,600
In Hebrews chapter 9, it says,

338
00:25:29,960 --> 00:25:33,260
And just as it is destined that each person dies only once,

339
00:25:33,760 --> 00:25:35,400
and after that comes judgment,

340
00:25:35,780 --> 00:25:39,700
so also Christ died only once as a sacrifice

341
00:25:39,700 --> 00:25:42,460
to take away the sins of many people.

342
00:25:43,490 --> 00:25:44,850
But does that seem fair?

343
00:25:45,350 --> 00:25:48,460
2 Peter 3.9, I think, handles the objection well.

344
00:25:49,200 --> 00:25:53,320
The Lord isn't really being slow about his promise to return,

345
00:25:53,760 --> 00:25:54,980
as some people think.

346
00:25:54,980 --> 00:25:57,480
No, he's being patient for your sake.

347
00:25:58,220 --> 00:25:59,980
He does not want anyone to perish.

348
00:26:00,360 --> 00:26:03,780
So he is giving more time for everyone to repent.

349
00:26:05,000 --> 00:26:07,760
And what I see in that scripture is that God is saying to us

350
00:26:07,760 --> 00:26:09,560
that no one is going to hell

351
00:26:09,560 --> 00:26:12,360
that would have made a decision to go to heaven

352
00:26:12,360 --> 00:26:13,760
if they just had a little more time.

353
00:26:14,370 --> 00:26:15,910
If there was one more chance,

354
00:26:16,170 --> 00:26:20,530
if somehow that accident would have only happened a day later,

355
00:26:20,570 --> 00:26:21,730
they would have made the decision.

356
00:26:22,520 --> 00:26:25,620
If their last breath came just a week too early,

357
00:26:25,780 --> 00:26:28,020
And somehow, if they just had a little more time,

358
00:26:28,200 --> 00:26:29,720
they would have made the right decision.

359
00:26:30,000 --> 00:26:32,100
In God's sovereignty, I'm seeing from the Scriptures

360
00:26:32,100 --> 00:26:34,580
that God is just and fair.

361
00:26:34,840 --> 00:26:36,820
And by the time a person ends up in hell,

362
00:26:36,820 --> 00:26:40,020
they have made that firm choice.

363
00:26:45,040 --> 00:26:47,080
And how can hell exist alongside heaven?

364
00:26:48,720 --> 00:26:50,940
How can the two be side by side?

365
00:26:51,020 --> 00:26:52,460
It's a great image that Eric created here.

366
00:26:53,260 --> 00:26:54,560
How do those two work together?

367
00:26:56,800 --> 00:27:01,040
C.S. Lewis, in fact, the author of the Reader's Theater we heard,

368
00:27:01,040 --> 00:27:04,990
said hell doesn't have veto power over heaven.

369
00:27:05,830 --> 00:27:07,930
He meant that people in heaven will not be denied

370
00:27:07,930 --> 00:27:09,510
the privilege of enjoying their life

371
00:27:09,510 --> 00:27:12,070
just because they're consciously aware of hell.

372
00:27:12,070 --> 00:27:16,130
If they couldn't, then hell would have veto power over heaven.

373
00:27:16,950 --> 00:27:18,030
And Moreland adds to this.

374
00:27:18,130 --> 00:27:21,430
He says, you have to remember that the soul is big enough

375
00:27:21,430 --> 00:27:25,730
to have an unperturbed sense of joy, well-being, love, and happiness

376
00:27:25,730 --> 00:27:29,790
while at the same time having a sense of grief and sadness for others.

377
00:27:30,590 --> 00:27:32,330
That that's not an inconsistent position.

378
00:27:32,750 --> 00:27:33,730
I mean, think about it this way.

379
00:27:34,090 --> 00:27:38,130
We saw images this morning of people hurting in South Africa.

380
00:27:38,490 --> 00:27:40,430
And our souls are pierced.

381
00:27:40,610 --> 00:27:44,070
Somehow we are drawn emotionally to that place and we hurt

382
00:27:44,070 --> 00:27:48,710
and we have a sense of grief over the sin, the evil in our world.

383
00:27:48,710 --> 00:27:52,070
At the same time, we can still love each other

384
00:27:52,070 --> 00:27:54,650
and enjoy being together the rest of this day.

385
00:27:55,350 --> 00:27:59,670
We can have our souls big enough to handle that kind of pain

386
00:27:59,670 --> 00:28:01,610
and still encounter joy.

387
00:28:03,060 --> 00:28:04,680
We can still have lunch this afternoon

388
00:28:04,680 --> 00:28:05,840
and enjoy each other

389
00:28:05,840 --> 00:28:07,360
while the realities of evil

390
00:28:07,360 --> 00:28:09,060
still exist in our world,

391
00:28:09,340 --> 00:28:10,040
in our nation.

392
00:28:10,860 --> 00:28:11,940
We think about the events

393
00:28:11,940 --> 00:28:13,340
of just a month and a half ago.

394
00:28:13,660 --> 00:28:14,880
We are deeply saddened

395
00:28:14,880 --> 00:28:16,300
by the tragedy in New York

396
00:28:16,300 --> 00:28:17,860
and by the evils perpetrated there.

397
00:28:18,060 --> 00:28:19,080
But life goes on

398
00:28:19,080 --> 00:28:21,300
and we're still able to hug a grandchild

399
00:28:21,300 --> 00:28:22,780
or a child or a loved one.

400
00:28:22,780 --> 00:28:25,180
We can still have joy and pain

401
00:28:25,180 --> 00:28:27,320
in our souls at the same time.

402
00:28:28,280 --> 00:28:30,280
And from that we extrapolate the concept

403
00:28:30,280 --> 00:28:32,300
that we can have heaven and hell

404
00:28:32,300 --> 00:28:33,920
is in two distinct places

405
00:28:33,920 --> 00:28:35,780
and we can still feel joy in heaven

406
00:28:35,780 --> 00:28:39,720
though there is pain over here in hell.

407
00:28:43,580 --> 00:28:45,400
Another challenge to the Christian faith

408
00:28:45,400 --> 00:28:47,160
is the idea of reincarnation.

409
00:28:50,240 --> 00:28:52,500
Kind of the recycling of the soul, if you will.

410
00:28:54,480 --> 00:28:56,820
Isn't that more rational than hell, some would argue?

411
00:28:59,290 --> 00:29:01,050
I think the concept of reincarnation,

412
00:29:01,310 --> 00:29:04,330
the idea that you die and you come back again

413
00:29:04,330 --> 00:29:05,450
in various forms,

414
00:29:06,400 --> 00:29:08,540
is really untenable philosophically.

415
00:29:08,540 --> 00:29:11,680
And I also find that it denies our fundamental personhood, and here's why.

416
00:29:12,020 --> 00:29:16,060
Because reincarnation, just real basically, as I'm going to state it,

417
00:29:16,840 --> 00:29:19,520
is the concept that we're moving towards moral perfection,

418
00:29:20,160 --> 00:29:22,560
and that we can come back in succeeding lives

419
00:29:22,560 --> 00:29:25,680
and kind of keep working towards that kind of perfection.

420
00:29:25,980 --> 00:29:28,560
But if you've really, if you will, blown it in this life,

421
00:29:28,580 --> 00:29:31,140
you come back in a lower form next time.

422
00:29:31,520 --> 00:29:35,360
And you might come back as a dog or a cat or maybe a doorknob or something,

423
00:29:35,360 --> 00:29:39,640
but everything is sort of in process of working upwards,

424
00:29:39,780 --> 00:29:41,120
but if you've blown it, you go backward,

425
00:29:41,280 --> 00:29:43,380
and you work your way back and forth.

426
00:29:43,660 --> 00:29:44,860
The problem is this.

427
00:29:45,460 --> 00:29:47,240
If you come back as an amoeba,

428
00:29:48,670 --> 00:29:52,160
what is essentially, who are you?

429
00:29:53,040 --> 00:29:55,580
Because Kirk has a body and a soul and a mind,

430
00:29:55,780 --> 00:29:57,100
there's an essence about me.

431
00:29:57,780 --> 00:29:59,160
When I come back as an amoeba,

432
00:29:59,360 --> 00:30:01,140
what is really essential to me?

433
00:30:02,740 --> 00:30:03,840
You see the challenge there.

434
00:30:04,420 --> 00:30:06,580
When you come back as an inanimate object, if you will,

435
00:30:06,580 --> 00:30:08,620
what is essential to me?

436
00:30:08,800 --> 00:30:09,840
What is essential to you?

437
00:30:09,980 --> 00:30:10,940
It doesn't work.

438
00:30:11,620 --> 00:30:13,380
And besides, you're turning over your soul

439
00:30:13,380 --> 00:30:15,500
into this great big wheel in the sky concept

440
00:30:15,500 --> 00:30:17,440
with no real personal God.

441
00:30:17,720 --> 00:30:20,500
It's just kind of this recycling model

442
00:30:20,500 --> 00:30:22,900
that doesn't really have any philosophical backbone.

443
00:30:24,140 --> 00:30:27,180
Hell, on the other hand, respects persons as persons.

444
00:30:30,470 --> 00:30:34,540
It doesn't violate the essential personhood of the person.

445
00:30:37,160 --> 00:30:39,380
I know I've given you a lot of information this morning.

446
00:30:39,480 --> 00:30:40,580
It'll be available on our website

447
00:30:40,580 --> 00:30:42,000
to take a look at this script.

448
00:30:43,060 --> 00:30:45,000
You can begin to digest it and think about it more.

449
00:30:45,500 --> 00:30:46,960
And there's so much more in that chapter

450
00:30:46,960 --> 00:30:49,000
from Strobel's book that I didn't even cover this morning.

451
00:30:49,040 --> 00:30:50,540
I just got some of the little fine points.

452
00:30:51,020 --> 00:30:52,060
But as I'm kind of wrapping up

453
00:30:52,060 --> 00:30:53,200
and coming in for a landing here,

454
00:30:54,060 --> 00:30:56,500
I want to say a few things more in conclusion.

455
00:30:56,960 --> 00:30:59,660
God, for one thing, takes no pleasure

456
00:30:59,660 --> 00:31:03,210
in the concept of people going to hell.

457
00:31:05,300 --> 00:31:06,760
Ezekiel 33 says this,

458
00:31:06,760 --> 00:31:08,980
As surely as I live, says the Sovereign Lord,

459
00:31:09,860 --> 00:31:12,440
I take no pleasure in the death of wicked people.

460
00:31:13,180 --> 00:31:16,260
I only want them to turn from their wicked ways so they can live.

461
00:31:16,680 --> 00:31:18,940
Turn, turn from your wickedness, O people of Israel.

462
00:31:19,340 --> 00:31:20,600
Why should you die?

463
00:31:22,460 --> 00:31:28,380
God is not turning the ratchets on the rack with a sadistic smile,

464
00:31:28,560 --> 00:31:31,150
enjoying the reality of hell.

465
00:31:32,240 --> 00:31:36,900
But hell is born out of God's justice and out of his respect for people.

466
00:31:36,900 --> 00:31:40,680
But he takes no pleasure in having people go there.

467
00:31:41,000 --> 00:31:47,530
So given all of this, finally, what is our response as Christians?

468
00:31:49,990 --> 00:31:52,850
And I want to put up a quote by Soren Kierkegaard, a Danish philosopher.

469
00:31:53,130 --> 00:31:53,550
He says,

470
00:31:54,630 --> 00:32:08,760
If we believe in hell, if we believe in what the scriptures say,

471
00:32:08,760 --> 00:32:13,120
if we believe it philosophically has teeth to believe in an afterlife

472
00:32:13,120 --> 00:32:14,860
that honors the personhood

473
00:32:14,860 --> 00:32:17,360
and our decisions that we forged in life,

474
00:32:17,540 --> 00:32:18,800
if we believe in that,

475
00:32:19,060 --> 00:32:20,340
then it is our responsibility

476
00:32:20,340 --> 00:32:23,140
to share with others that reality.

477
00:32:24,560 --> 00:32:26,340
To be Jacob Marley, if you will,

478
00:32:26,340 --> 00:32:27,640
and tell Scrooge,

479
00:32:27,940 --> 00:32:29,880
don't forge these chains.

480
00:32:30,480 --> 00:32:33,440
Stop, turn, and go a different way.

481
00:32:36,620 --> 00:32:37,580
To look to Jesus,

482
00:32:38,680 --> 00:32:40,160
the one who can make us clean

483
00:32:40,160 --> 00:32:41,660
and allow us into heaven.

484
00:32:42,000 --> 00:32:43,680
To make us the kind of people

485
00:32:43,680 --> 00:32:45,340
that would enjoy heaven.

486
00:32:45,880 --> 00:32:47,780
Friends, God has entrusted us

487
00:32:47,780 --> 00:32:49,660
to share the message of heaven

488
00:32:49,660 --> 00:32:51,700
and, on the flip side,

489
00:32:51,800 --> 00:32:53,280
to share the message of hell.

490
00:32:53,420 --> 00:32:55,600
Jesus talked about it an awful lot in Scripture.

491
00:32:56,200 --> 00:32:57,880
Jesus was always telling people

492
00:32:57,880 --> 00:33:00,920
to repent and to follow Him.

493
00:33:01,990 --> 00:33:03,770
And that becomes our charge as well,

494
00:33:03,770 --> 00:33:06,250
that we tell people to repent

495
00:33:06,250 --> 00:33:08,540
and follow Jesus.

496
00:33:10,840 --> 00:33:12,240
And so with that, we close in prayer.

497
00:33:13,710 --> 00:33:14,570
Our Father and our God.

